We apply the Euclidean Algorithm to find gcd$(b^2 + 9b + 30, b + 6)$.
\begin{align*}
\text{gcd}(b^2 + 9b + 30, b + 6) &= \text{gcd}(b^2 + 9b + 30 - (b + 5)(b + 6), b + 6) \\
&= \text{gcd}(b^2 + 9b + 30 - (b^2 + 11b + 30), b + 6) \\
&= \text{gcd}(-2b, b + 6).
\end{align*}
The expression now simplifies to:
\begin{align*}
\text{gcd}(-2b, b + 6) &= \text{gcd}(2b, b + 6) = 2 \cdot \text{gcd}(b, b + 6) \\
&= 2 \cdot \text{gcd}(6, b + 6) \quad \text{(since } b \text{ is a multiple of } 2160 \text{, and } 2160 \text{ is a multiple of } 6\text{)} \\
&= 2 \cdot 6 = 12.
\end{align*}
Thus, the greatest common divisor is $\boxed{12}$.

