Solution. Let the median $TA$ intersect side $BC$ at point $A'$. The line passing through $Q$ and parallel to $BC$ intersects the median $AA'$ at point $N$, and the line passing through $P$ and parallel to $BC$ intersects the median $AA'$ and side $AC$ at points $M$ and $P'$, respectively. Let $TA' = a$, $TA = 2a$, $TM = xa$, and $TN = ya$. Since $\triangle QTN \sim \triangle PTM$ and $PM = MP'$, we have

$$
\frac{TN}{TM} = \frac{QN}{MP} = \frac{QN}{MP'} = \frac{NA}{MA} = \frac{NT + TA}{TA - MT}
$$

![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2024_06_05_be301a4ad5d08b3cf1d5g-1.jpg?height=659&width=548&top_left_y=668&top_left_x=901)

Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{ya}{xa} = \frac{ya + 2a}{2a - xa}, \quad \frac{y}{x} = \frac{y + 2}{2 - x}, \quad y = x(y + 1) \\
& \frac{y}{x} = y + 1, \quad \frac{ya}{xa} = 1 + \frac{ya}{a}, \quad \frac{TN}{TM} = 1 + \frac{TN}{TA'}
\end{aligned}
$$

However, since $\triangle QTN \sim \triangle PTM$, we have $\frac{TN}{TM} = \frac{TQ}{TP}$, and since $\triangle QTN \sim \triangle RTA'$, we have $\frac{TN}{TA'} = \frac{TQ}{TR}$. Therefore, from $\frac{TN}{TM} = 1 + \frac{TN}{TA'}$, it follows that $\frac{TQ}{TP} = 1 + \frac{TQ}{TR}$, which means $\frac{1}{TP} = \frac{1}{TQ} + \frac{1}{TR}$.

