First, we simplify the expression for $z$.
\begin{align*}
z &= \frac{1-i}{1+i} + 2i \\
&= \frac{(1-i)^2}{(1+i)(1-i)} + 2i \quad (\text{Multiply numerator and denominator by } (1-i)) \\
&= \frac{1 - 2i + i^2}{1 - i^2} + 2i \\
&= \frac{1 - 2i - 1}{1 + 1} + 2i \quad (\text{Since } i^2 = -1) \\
&= \frac{-2i}{2} + 2i \\
&= -i + 2i \\
&= \boxed{i}
\end{align*}

Now, we find the magnitude of $z$. The magnitude of a complex number $a + bi$ is given by $\sqrt{a^2 + b^2}$. In this case, $z = 0 + 1i$, so:
\begin{align*}
|z| &= \sqrt{0^2 + 1^2} \\
&= \sqrt{1} \\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}

