1) The given fraction is improper, so we first separate the integer part.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 2 x^{4}-13 x^{3}+32 x^{2}-24 x+1 \left\lvert\, \frac{x^{3}-5 x^{2}+6 x}{2 x-3}\right. \\
& \frac{2 x^{4}-10 x^{3}+12 x^{2}}{-3 x^{3}+20 x^{2}-24 x+1} \\
& \quad \frac{-3 x^{3}+15 x^{2}-18 x}{5 x^{2}-6 x+1}
\end{aligned}
$$

We get $\frac{2 x^{4}-13 x^{3}+32 x^{2}-24 x+1}{x^{3}-5 x^{2}+6 x}=2 x-3+\frac{5 x^{2}-6 x+1}{x^{3}-5 x^{2}+6 x}$.

2) It remains to decompose the fraction on the right side of this equation into simpler fractions, for which we first factor the denominator of this fraction into simple factors.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{5 x^{2}-6 x+1}{x(x-3)(x-2)}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{x-3}+ & \frac{C}{x-2}= \\
& =\frac{A(x-3)(x-2)+B x(x-2)+C x(x-3)}{x(x-3)(x-2)}
\end{aligned}
$$

We equate the coefficients of the same powers of the numerators in the right and left fractions. This leads to a linear system of three equations with three unknowns $A, B$, and $C$.

$$
\left\{\begin{array} { l } 
{ x ^ { 2 } : A + B + C = 5 } \\
{ x ^ { 1 } : - 5 A - 2 B - 3 C = - 6 , } \\
{ x ^ { 0 } : 6 A = 1 \Rightarrow A = 1 / 6 }
\end{array} \Rightarrow \left\{\begin{array} { l } 
{ B + C = \frac { 2 9 } { 6 } , } \\
{ 2 B + 3 C = \frac { 3 1 } { 6 } }
\end{array} \Rightarrow \left\{\begin{array}{l}
A=\frac{1}{6} \\
B=\frac{28}{3} \\
C=-\frac{9}{2}
\end{array}\right.\right.\right.
$$

Answer. $\frac{2 x^{4}-13 x^{3}+32 x^{2}-24 x+1}{x^{3}-5 x^{2}+6 x}=2 x-3+\frac{1}{6 x}+\frac{28}{3(x-3)}-\frac{9}{2(x-2)}$.

