(1) If $a \parallel \alpha$, $b \parallel \beta$, then $a \parallel b$; this proposition is incorrect because two lines parallel to two different planes can be intersecting, parallel, or skew;  
(2) If $a \parallel \alpha$, $b \perp \alpha$, then $a \perp b$; a line perpendicular to a plane must be perpendicular to any line parallel to that plane, so this proposition is correct;  
(3) If $a \parallel b$, $b \parallel \alpha$, then $a \parallel \alpha$; this proposition is incorrect, under these conditions, $a$ could be within $\alpha$;  
(4) If $a \perp \alpha$, $a \parallel \beta$, then $\alpha \perp \beta$; this proposition is correct because if $a \parallel \beta$, there exists a line within $\beta$ parallel to $a$, and since $a \perp \alpha$, this line is also perpendicular to $\alpha$, thus $\alpha \perp \beta$.  
In summary, the correct proposition numbers are (2) and (4).  
Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{(2)(4)}$.

